---
import ContentLayout from '../layouts/ContentLayout.astro';

const SITE = 'https://gokhangunduz.github.io/alpha';

const schema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'BreadcrumbList',
  itemListElement: [
    { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 1, name: 'Home',  item: `${SITE}/` },
    { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 2, name: 'About', item: `${SITE}/about` },
  ],
};
---

<ContentLayout
  title="About — alpha"
  description="The story behind alpha: a VS Code theme that pairs GitHub's interface with an isoluminant syntax palette."
  canonical={`${SITE}/about`}
  activeNav="about"
  heading="About"
  subtitle="A VS Code theme built around two ideas: a familiar interface, and a palette where every color carries the same weight."
  schema={schema}
>
  <h2>What alpha is</h2>
  <p><strong>alpha</strong> is a Visual Studio Code color theme shipped in two variants — <strong>alpha dark</strong> and <strong>alpha light</strong>. The interface chrome (editor, sidebar, status bar, tabs, panels, terminal, git decorations) is sourced from the official GitHub themes at v6.3.5 and matched byte-for-byte. On top of that familiar surface, alpha replaces the syntax palette with seven hues tuned for equal perceived weight.</p>

  <h2>The palette</h2>
  <p>In the <strong>dark variant</strong>, every syntax color is locked at <strong>HSL(h, 100%, 68%)</strong>. Only the hue rotates. The result is strictly isoluminant — no token visually outweighs another, so the eye reads structure instead of brightness.</p>
  <p>In the <strong>light variant</strong>, the same seven hues are retuned per channel: saturation stays at 100%, but lightness is lowered until each color clears <strong>≥ 4.5:1 contrast (WCAG-AA)</strong> on a white background. The variants look different, but they feel the same.</p>

  <h2>Why a GitHub-matched UI</h2>
  <p>The VS Code chrome is a solved problem. GitHub already publishes themes that pair well with GitHub.com, GitHub Desktop, and a thousand other tools developers use every day. alpha doesn't reinvent that — it adopts it, exactly, and spends its design budget where it matters: the code itself.</p>

  <h2>About the developer</h2>
  <p>alpha is designed and maintained by <a href="https://gokhangunduz.dev" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>Gökhan Gündüz</strong></a>, an independent developer based in Ankara, Turkey. The theme is free, open source under the MIT License, and developed in public on <a href="https://github.com/gokhangunduz/alpha" target="_blank" rel="noopener">GitHub</a>.</p>
</ContentLayout>
